### 1. One-Line Summary
* Hurricane 3 Neo: A tacky, hard, “boostable” Chinese-style rubber that rewards full strokes with heavy spin and a loaded first ball, but demands technique and commitment.
* Dignics 80: A modern ESN/Japanese-style high-tension rubber with a grippy topsheet and springy sponge that’s easier to access across gears, excelling in fast topspin and counterplay.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Slower and more “dead” on light touch; you must engage the sponge for pace.
        * Dignics 80: Noticeably bouncier; easy depth with compact strokes and small acceleration.
    * **Top End:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Very high when fully engaged (especially if boosted); thrives on big swings and body-driven power.
        * Dignics 80: High top speed with less effort; strong on mid-distance countering without needing maximum stroke length.
    * **Linearity:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: More linear once you commit; low-to-mid gears feel muted, then it “turns on” with strong acceleration.
        * Dignics 80: More catapult-driven; stronger built-in rebound can feel less linear in the short-to-mid range.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Elite vs backspin—tacky topsheet bites early, enabling very heavy, high-quality openers if you brush and drive.
        * Dignics 80: Easier lift with less effort; excellent opener quality, but typically less “tacky bite” on the first ball than H3 Neo.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Higher ceiling on pure rotational “heaviness” when you accelerate and graze; signature heavy, dipping ball.
        * Dignics 80: Very high, especially on power topspin; peak spin is close, but the feeling is more “grip + speed” than “tacky drag.”
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Tacky grip helps slow-roll and spinny serves; can be sensitive to dust and needs upkeep for best bite.
        * Dignics 80: Strong mechanical grip; very consistent in rallies and less dependent on tackiness maintenance.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Generally medium-to-high arc when brushed well; can be flatter if you drive more than brush.
        * Dignics 80: Medium arc with a “direct” trajectory; tends to be more point-and-shoot in counters.
    * **Safety:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: High safety on heavy-brush loops (arc + spin), but low-commitment strokes can drop short.
        * Dignics 80: High safety through easy depth and stable topspin; short game requires discipline due to bounce.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Hard, crisp, and “connected” to the ball; clearer feedback on brush vs drive contact.
        * Dignics 80: Springy, solid, and modern; strong impact feel but more “built-in” rebound sensation.
    * **Dwell:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Longer perceived dwell on brush contact; helps shape heavy spin and placement.
        * Dignics 80: Medium dwell; holds enough for confidence, but releases quicker for speed-oriented exchanges.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Less sensitive to incoming spin on passive touch because it’s less bouncy; easier to keep the ball short.
        * Dignics 80: More sensitive due to higher rebound and grip; needs finer angle control on receive.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Excellent for short push, stop, and heavy short underspin; “dead” feel helps keep it tight.
        * Dignics 80: Very capable but requires softer hands; tends to pop up if you’re not absorbing the bounce.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Stable and low-bounce, but can lack “free” pace—blocks may sit up if you don’t firm the contact.
        * Dignics 80: Strong—catapult gives depth easily; very reliable for compact blocks and quick redirects.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * Hurricane 3 Neo: Excellent when you engage forward and through; rewards timing and full-body counterlooping.
        * Dignics 80: Outstanding for topspin-to-topspin; fast, direct, and forgiving for punchy counters.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Hurricane 3 Neo if:**
    * You prioritize first-ball dominance: heavy serve, heavy receive, heavy opening loop vs backspin.
    * You use full strokes, strong acceleration, and like a harder, more “connected” feel.
    * You want superior short game control and spin variation, and you’re okay with higher technique demands (and possible boosting/maintenance habits).
* **Choose Dignics 80 if:**
    * You want a top-level “do-everything” rubber with easier access to speed and spin across gears.
    * Your game is built on fast topspin, blocking, and countering with compact technique.
    * You prefer consistency and performance without tuning, and can manage a livelier short game.